istic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Beatrix","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Late Latin personal name, which was borne by a saint martyred in Rome, together with Saints Faustinus and Simplicius, in the early 4th century. The original form of the name was probably <i>Viatrix</i>, a feminine version of <i>Viator</i> ‘voyager (through life)’, which was a favourite name among early Christians. This was then altered by association with Latin <i>Beatus</i> ‘blessed’ (<i>Via-</i> and <i>Bea-</i> sometimes being pronounced the same in Late Latin).  See also  Beatrice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Beatrix de Rosières was born in 1107, her father, Sieur Gaucher de Rosières, was 45 and her mother, Alix De Nesle Carolingien, was 32. She married Dagobert d'Encre in 1124. They were the parents of at least 4 daughters. She died in 1167, in Albert, Somme, Picardie, France, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1107–1167":"1107–1167","1091–1142":"1091–1142","1096–1147":"1096–1147","1104–1151":"1104–1151","1105–1165":"1105–1165","1127–1185":"1127–1185","1132–1194":"1132–1194","1134–1189":"1134–1189","1140–1197":"1140–1197","1062–1124":"1062–1124","1075–1122":"1075–1122","1091":"1091","1132":"1132","1165":"1165","1197":"1197","1142":"1142","1075":"1075","1185":"1185","1140":"1140","1151":"1151","1096":"1096","1062":"1062","1194":"1194","1107":"1107","1127":"1127","1105